              'Duncan\'s warm greeting to Macbeth drips with dramatic irony — he is addressing the man who is already contemplating his murder as his "worthiest" kinsman. The term "cousin" emphasises the family bond between them, which makes Macbeth\'s crime not just regicide but also a betrayal of kinship. This short exclamation encapsulates Duncan\'s generous, trusting nature and the terrible gap between how he perceives Macbeth and what Macbeth truly intends. Every warm word from Duncan makes the audience more aware of the approaching horror.'
