    // ---- CONTEXT POINTS ----
    contextPoints: [
      'King James I, who reigned when Shakespeare wrote Macbeth (c.1606), was fascinated by witchcraft and wrote "Daemonologie" (1597), which directly influenced Shakespeare\'s portrayal of the Weird Sisters.',
      'The Gunpowder Plot of 1605, in which Catholic conspirators attempted to assassinate James I, made themes of regicide, treason, and equivocation highly topical and politically sensitive.',
      'The Divine Right of Kings was a central political doctrine: monarchs were believed to be God\'s appointed rulers, making regicide not just a political crime but a sin against God.',
      'The Great Chain of Being was the Jacobean belief that all creation existed in a fixed hierarchy (God > angels > monarch > nobility > commoners > animals). Disrupting this chain through regicide would cause chaos in nature itself.',
      'Shakespeare\'s portrayal of Banquo as noble and virtuous was likely influenced by the fact that King James I claimed descent from Banquo — the historical Banquo was actually complicit in Duncan\'s murder according to Holinshed\'s Chronicles.',
      'Jacobean society had rigid gender roles: women were expected to be submissive, gentle, and maternal. Lady Macbeth\'s rejection of these qualities would have been profoundly shocking and would have marked her as unnatural.',
      'The play draws on Holinshed\'s "Chronicles of England, Scotland, and Ireland" (1577), Shakespeare\'s primary historical source, though he significantly altered the story for dramatic and political purposes.',
      'Equivocation — saying something that is technically true but deliberately misleading — was a major contemporary issue linked to the trial of Jesuit priest Father Henry Garnet after the Gunpowder Plot.',
      'Macbeth is Shakespeare\'s shortest tragedy, and its compressed, relentless pace mirrors the spiralling psychological deterioration of its protagonist. The play moves from order to chaos with terrifying speed, reflecting the Jacobean fear that political stability could be destroyed in an instant.',
      'The play was likely performed at the Globe Theatre and possibly also at court for King James I. The indoor performance space of the Blackfriars Theatre, which Shakespeare\'s company acquired in 1608, would have enhanced the play\'s dark atmosphere with candlelight and enclosed acoustics.',
      'Sleep was considered sacred in Jacobean culture — a gift from God that restored body and mind. Macbeth\'s destruction of sleep through his crimes therefore represents a violation of the natural, divinely-ordained order of human existence.',
      'The role of Lady Macbeth would have been played by a boy actor in Shakespeare\'s theatre, as women were not permitted to perform on the English stage until after the Restoration in 1660. This adds an additional layer of gender performance to a character who is already deliberately performing a version of masculinity through her "unsex me" speech and her manipulation of her husband.',
      'The number three was considered mystical and ominous in Jacobean culture. Shakespeare uses three witches, Macbeth receives three prophecies in Act 1 and three apparitions in Act 4, and the structure of temptation, crime, and punishment follows a tripartite pattern that mirrors Christian theology of sin, fall, and judgement.'
    ],

