      'Pay close attention to Shakespeare\'s use of dramatic irony — moments where the audience knows more than the characters. For instance, Duncan praising Macbeth\'s castle as pleasant while the audience knows he will be murdered there. Identifying and analysing dramatic irony demonstrates sophisticated understanding of how Shakespeare manipulates the audience\'s experience.',
      'When discussing the witches, avoid simplistic statements like "people in Jacobean times believed in witches." Instead, explore the nuance: James I both feared witchcraft and was sceptical of some claims, and Shakespeare\'s play reflects this ambiguity by leaving open the question of whether the witches genuinely control events or merely exploit existing human weaknesses.'
