          'Shakespeare uses a pervasive pattern of light and darkness imagery throughout Romeo and Juliet that operates on multiple symbolic levels. Romeo consistently associates Juliet with light — she "doth teach the torches to burn bright", she is "the sun" that makes "the envious moon" pale, and her eyes are like "two of the fairest stars in all the heaven." This imagery elevates Juliet above the ordinary world and presents their love as something luminous and transcendent. However, Shakespeare creates a powerful paradox: almost all of Romeo and Juliet\'s significant scenes take place at night — the balcony scene, their wedding night, and their deaths in the tomb. Their love can only flourish in darkness, hidden from the hostile daylight world of feuding families and social expectation. The darkness provides them with privacy and freedom from their public identities as Montague and Capulet, but it also symbolises the danger and secrecy that surround their relationship. Juliet\'s epithalamium — "Come, gentle night, come, loving, black-browed night" — is a beautiful invocation of darkness as a space of intimacy and erotic freedom. Yet darkness is also associated with death throughout the play: the tomb, the poison, the dagger. Shakespeare uses this dual symbolism to reinforce the play\'s central tragic irony: the same conditions that allow love to flourish (secrecy, darkness, intensity) are also those that lead to its destruction. The play\'s final image — the promise of golden statues that will "shine" — suggests that only in death can Romeo and Juliet\'s love finally exist in the light, visible to all.'
