          'The Nurse is one of the most vivid and dramatically important characters in Romeo and Juliet, serving as Juliet\'s closest confidante, surrogate mother, and comic counterpoint to the elevated language of the lovers. She has been with Juliet since birth — having nursed her as a baby — and her rambling, bawdy recollections in Act 1, Scene 3 about Juliet\'s childhood reveal a deep, affectionate bond that is warmer and more intimate than anything Juliet shares with her biological mother. The Nurse\'s language is characterised by earthy, sexual humour and a pragmatic, unromantic view of love that contrasts sharply with the spiritual, poetic language of Romeo and Juliet. She enthusiastically facilitates the secret marriage, acting as a go-between for the lovers with a mixture of excitement and comic self-importance. However, the Nurse\'s ultimate betrayal of Juliet — advising her to forget Romeo and marry Paris after Romeo\'s banishment — reveals the limitations of her loyalty and understanding. Her pragmatic argument that Paris is "a lovely gentleman" and that "Romeo\'s a dishclout to him" shows she fundamentally does not understand the depth of Juliet\'s love. This betrayal leaves Juliet completely isolated, with no adult she can trust, and drives her toward the Friar\'s desperate sleeping-potion plan. Shakespeare uses the Nurse to demonstrate the gap between the practical, compromising world of adults and the absolute, uncompromising passion of the young lovers. Her comic presence in the first half of the play makes her absence from the tragic second half all the more noticeable, mirroring the play\'s shift from comedy to tragedy.',
