      'Consider the role of time: the entire play takes place over just four days, and this compression of time creates a sense of urgency and inevitability. Every delay (the missed letter) and rush (Romeo\'s impulsive actions) drives the tragedy.',
      'Use the extract to launch into wider discussion — analyse the passage closely, then connect it to events, characters, and themes elsewhere in the play to demonstrate whole-text knowledge.',
      'Engage with the Prologue as a structural device: it creates dramatic irony throughout the play, since the audience knows the lovers will die. Every joyful moment is therefore tinged with tragedy for the audience, even if not for the characters.',
      'For top marks, consider multiple interpretations: is the play primarily about fate or about the failures of the adults? Is Romeo and Juliet\'s love genuine maturity or youthful recklessness? Acknowledging complexity shows sophisticated understanding.',
