      'When discussing the ending, consider how the Prince\'s final speech frames the tragedy as a story with a moral purpose. The golden statues promised by the fathers transform the private love of Romeo and Juliet into a public monument — but Shakespeare leaves the audience to question whether this gesture is adequate reparation for the loss of two young lives.'
